The basic innovation of crypto is the production=C2=A0of artificial scarcit=
y. The original Bitcoin white paper=C2=A0addresses the problem: Sure, anyon=
e can type numbers on their computer, but is there a way for a community to=
 allocate numbers on your computer=C2=A0in a way that makes them demonstrab=
ly scarce? If there is, then you can call those numbers =E2=80=9Cmoney=E2=
=80=9D and they can be valuable. I am being a little annoying, but this was=
 obviously a real innovation and did in fact help make=C2=A0Bitcoin very va=
luable.=C2=A0The rest of the crypto world continued applying that same proc=
ess. Most non-fungible token projects address the problem: Sure, anyone can=
 limitlessly reproduce JPEGs on the internet, but is there a way for a comm=
unity to allocate ownership claims to JPEGs in a way that makes them scarce=
? The answer is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not really, no, in=C2=A0the sense that anyon=
e can still right-click and save the JPEGs underlying most of the popular N=
FT projects. And yet the answer is also =E2=80=9Csort of,=E2=80=9D in the s=
ense that NFT communities tend to respect the allocations of ownership clai=
ms; they=C2=A0act like=C2=A0the JPEGs are scarce =E2=80=94=C2=A0the NFTs, t=
he ownership claims,=C2=A0are=C2=A0scarce =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so they have v=
alue. And so some NFTs sell for lots of money.Basically it is easy, using b=
lockchain technology,=C2=A0to create=C2=A0scarce claims. You could I suppos=
e use this technology to create scarce claims to scarce resources: You coul=
d put, like, housing deeds or shares of corporate ownership=C2=A0or cargo-c=
ontainer manifests on the blockchain. This would =E2=80=94=C2=A0people have=
 argued for years=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0have benefits in terms of efficiency =
and legibility and tradability. It would create value by improving the proc=
esses by which real-world assets are transferred and allocated. Classic fin=
ancial-services stuff. Nobody talks that=C2=A0much about this anymore.Inste=
ad, people like to use blockchain technology to create scarce claims to=C2=
=A0abundant, or=C2=A0infinite, resources. There is absolutely no shortage o=
f JPEGs, they are infinitely reproducible more or less for free, but that m=
eans =E2=80=94 or meant =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you couldn=E2=80=99t become a m=
illionaire by having good taste in JPEGs. But now people can create a uniqu=
e non-fungible token=C2=A0representing ownership of a JPEG and use it as a =
status symbol or a speculative asset. Nobody will pay you for a number in y=
our computer=E2=80=99s memory, but people will pay you for a=C2=A0scarce=C2=
=A0number in your computer=E2=80=99s memory.It is an interesting economic q=
uestion whether this artificial production of scarcity could actually creat=
e value.=C2=A0Arguably abundance is more valuable than scarcity? Arguably t=
his is all =E2=80=A6=C2=A0terrible? Here is Ryan Broderick on crypto, Web3,=
 right-clicking on NFT JPEGs, etc.:The best overall articulation I=E2=80=99=
ve seen so far of why Web3 is so hated by many online subcultures right now=
 was from @nicodotgay, the Twitter user behind the right-click mosaic. They=
 explained in a follow-up tweet that they weren=E2=80=99t anti-NFT for ecol=
ogical reasons. =E2=80=9CThe real issue is that they represent an attempt t=
o re-impose artificial scarcity on culture,=E2=80=9D @nicodotgay tweeted. =
=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Digital scarcity=E2=80=99 is an anti human evolution ideo=
logy that imposes board game-like rules which serve no purpose than to pres=
erve the game itself - to hide the internal contradictions of capitalism th=
at become painfully obvious in an area of culture that has overcome scarcit=
y.=E2=80=9DBut the other way to put that is that people do seem to enjoy st=
atus-competition and gambling games, they get some value out of them, and a=
rtificial scarcity allows them to play a lot more of those games, thus incr=
easing human happiness, or something. There is a new abundance of scarcity.=
Similarly. There is a new coronavirus variant of concern, referred to as =
=E2=80=9Comicron.=E2=80=9D Let=E2=80=99s say you predict that omicron will =
be a really big deal, and you would like to make a bet on that prediction. =
There are various=C2=A0ways to implement that bet using regular financial a=
ssets =E2=80=94=C2=A0buy mask manufacturers or short cruise lines or whatev=
er =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they each involve real-world details; you need to pre=
dict some mechanism to link =E2=80=9Comicron will be a big deal=E2=80=9D to=
 =E2=80=9Ccruise-ship stocks will go down=E2=80=9D or whatever. What you wa=
nt is a pure bet on the proposition =E2=80=9Comicron will be a big deal.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0For instance if you could just buy the word =E2=80=9Comicron=E2=
=80=9D and collect a royalty every time someone used it, that would be alon=
g the lines of the bet that you want. If omicron is a big deal, people will=
 say =E2=80=9Comicron=E2=80=9D a lot and you=E2=80=99ll get lots of royalti=
es. You can=E2=80=99t do that. The word =E2=80=9Comicron=E2=80=9D is just a=
 word.[1] It=E2=80=99s not scarce.[2] Omicron omicron omicron omicron omicr=
on omicron omicron. See?On the other hand, because crypto gives you the too=
ls to create artificial scarcity,=C2=A0you could easily=C2=A0make=C2=A0a sc=
arce class of =E2=80=9Comicrons.=E2=80=9D Create a new crypto token on some=
 blockchain. =E2=80=9COnly 10,000 of this Omicron Coin will ever be minted,=
=E2=80=9D or whatever. Now you have a scarce version of the word omicron, a=
nd you can start ascribing value to it. The more people say =E2=80=9Comicro=
n,=E2=80=9D the more people will look to buy Omicron Coin, and the more val=
uable it will be.You probably hate me for typing that, but I promise that y=
ou don=E2=80=99t hate me as much as I hate myself. I know that it makes no =
sense! It=E2=80=99s just true, is all! Here=E2=80=99s my Bloomberg Opinion =
colleague  Mark Gongloff:A crypto thing called Omicron has soared more than=
 900% since Saturday because there is now also a Covid variant called omicr=
on. That's it. That's the reason.=C2=A0 ...Omicron the Crypto Thing is, in =
the words of CoinTelegraph, =E2=80=9Ca recently introduced decentralized re=
serve currency protocol that runs on the Ethereum layer-two network Arbitru=
m. Its native OMIC token is backed by several other crypto assets including=
 the USD Coin stablecoin and liquidity provider tokens. It can only be trad=
ed on the SushiSwap decentralized exchange.=E2=80=9DOmicron is a clone of O=
lympusDAO, a fascinating decentralized-finance Ponzi scheme that we=E2=80=
=99ll probably have to talk about around here one day, but that=E2=80=99s n=
ot why it=E2=80=99s up. It=E2=80=99s up because it is a tradable=C2=A0claim=
 with the word =E2=80=9Comicron=E2=80=9D in its name,=C2=A0and the word =E2=
=80=9Comicron=E2=80=9D is up. You just have to unfocus your eyes and not th=
ink too hard about it. Omicron, omicron, get it?I  wrote last month:All I a=
m saying is that if I sold you a crypto token that was called =E2=80=9CStri=
peCoin=E2=80=9D and I said =E2=80=9Cthis is a token on the stock of Stripe=
=E2=80=9D you might say =E2=80=94=C2=A0because you are reading Money Stuff,=
 etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might say =E2=80=9Cwait how is the value of the to=
ken linked to the value of Stripe=E2=80=9D and I would say =E2=80=9Chahahah=
a it absolutely isn=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D But my hypothesis is that not every=
one is as skeptical and literal-minded as you are, and some people would ju=
st go buy StripeCoin=C2=A0when they had nice thoughts about Stripe and sell=
 StripeCoin=C2=A0when they had sad thoughts about Stripe and buy a whole lo=
t of StripeCoin=C2=A0when Stripe went public,=C2=A0and it would at least di=
rectionally end up being a sort of a proxy for Stripe stock. And everyone w=
ould get what they came for, which is a convenient way to gamble on people=
=E2=80=99s feelings about Stripe.=C2=A0This model was wrong in one importan=
t respect: People did not buy Omicron because they have nice thoughts about=
 the omicron variant; they bought=C2=A0Omicron because they are having=C2=
=A0thoughts=C2=A0about it. (Presumably sad thoughts, it being a deadly viru=
s, though who knows.) The thing being traded here is not=C2=A0fondness=C2=
=A0but=C2=A0attention. Crypto has developed tools to create scarce claims o=
n computerized representations of memes, to create scarce tradable claims o=
n=C2=A0societal attention.[3] This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0extremely, extremely s=
tupid? I think? But what do I know. The point is that=C2=A0it works.Elsewhe=
re!The latest hot real-estate market isn=E2=80=99t on the scenic coasts or =
in balmy Sunbelt cities. It=E2=80=99s in the metaverse, where gamers are fl=
ocking and digital property sales are setting new records.A growing number =
of investment firms are acquiring digital land in worlds such as the Sandbo=
x and Decentraland, where players simulate real-life pursuits, from shoppin=
g to attending a concert. They are betting that individuals and companies w=
ill spend money to use virtual homes and retail space and that the value of=
 properties will increase as more people join the worlds.Sure!
