      Derivatives
   =20
 =20
Yesterday Francine McKenna wrote=C2=A0about the dispute between Tesla Inc. =
and JPMorgan Chase & Co. over some Tesla warrants that we  discussed a coup=
le of weeks ago. Her main point is that JPMorgan=C2=A0valued the warrants a=
t one price (assuming that they were adjusted for Elon Musk=E2=80=99s prete=
nd takeover of Tesla), Tesla valued them at some other price (assuming that=
 they weren=E2=80=99t), they are now in a legal fight over who was right, a=
nd PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP audits both companies=E2=80=99 books and pres=
umably let them both use their own differing valuations. This actually does=
 not bother me that much =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes companies get in valuatio=
n disputes, and anyway Tesla and JPMorgan account for Tesla warrants differ=
ently (JPMorgan as a mark-to-market asset, Tesla as an equity instrument) =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but that=E2=80=99s not what I want to talk about.Instead I w=
ant to talk about this sentence describing the initial 2014 transaction tha=
t Tesla and JPMorgan are now fighting over: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s one of th=
ose =E2=80=98heads I win, tails you lose=E2=80=99 type of deals investment =
banks talk seemingly sophisticated company treasurers into.=E2=80=9D I disa=
gree! JPMorgan=E2=80=99s=C2=A0adjustment=C2=A0of the warrants is controvers=
ial =E2=80=94=C2=A0Tesla thinks it was pretty opportunistic, and I have som=
e sympathy for that position =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the original deal was fine.=
 Tesla paid its banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0JPMorgan and three other underwriters =
on its 2014 convertible-bond deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0a net premium of about $21=
4 million for the transaction[4]; in exchange, Tesla got a =E2=80=9Cbond he=
dge=E2=80=9D (an option to buy its stock at the conversion price of the con=
vertible bond) and the banks got a warrant=C2=A0(an option to buy the stock=
 at a higher price). Net, Tesla bought a call spread on its own stock. By t=
he 2021 maturity of=C2=A0the=C2=A0convertible bonds, the stock was way abov=
e the exercise prices of all of the options, and Tesla saved something like=
 $760 million worth of stock issuance because of the call spread.[5] Now JP=
Morgan wants $160 million of that back, but even so it was a good deal=C2=
=A0for Tesla. (The banks did fine too, they were hedged, don=E2=80=99t worr=
y about them.)But it gets better. The net premium that Tesla paid to the ba=
nks was about $214 million. As we  discussed last week, that number is conv=
eniently almost exactly the amount of taxes that Tesla could theoretically =
save by doing this transaction: The price it paid for the bond hedge (about=
 $603 million) was tax-deductible, while the price the banks paid it for th=
e warrants (about $389 million) was not taxable; at a 35% tax rate that $60=
3 million deduction should be worth about $211 million. In practice Tesla h=
as mostly generated losses since 2014, and probably didn=E2=80=99t get to t=
ake a lot of those tax deductions; also corporate tax rates are lower now. =
In general, though, this is the sort of transaction that could reasonably h=
ave been marketed as =E2=80=9Cyou buy an option from us and the IRS pays fo=
r it.=E2=80=9DI am harping on this because I think it is a general theme in=
 the analysis of complicated financial transactions. In general, when you s=
ee a bank sell a complex derivative to a non-financial customer like a car =
company,=C2=A0there are two popular ways to analyze it:=09The textbook view=
=C2=A0is that the company has some financial risk and is paying the bank a =
fair premium to manage the risk. =E2=80=9CTesla has a risk that its stock w=
ill go up above the conversion price, so it paid its banks to hedge that ri=
sk.=E2=80=9D (It is right in the name, =E2=80=9Cbond hedge.=E2=80=9D)=09The=
=C2=A0cynical view=C2=A0is that the bank has tricked the customer into givi=
ng the bank a lot of money for a worthless thing that the customer doesn=E2=
=80=99t understand, that the way the bank makes money is by bamboozling the=
 client in a zero-sum trade.I think you should be suspicious of both of tho=
se views. In many cases the=C2=A0correct, though also cynical=C2=A0view is =
that the trade is, deep down, a=C2=A0tax optimization: The bank does stuff =
to lower the customer=E2=80=99s taxes, and the customer gives the bank a cu=
t of the tax savings.[6]
