om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Omicron</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic innovation of crypto is the =
production=C2=A0of artificial scarcity. The original <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25879753.286657/aHR0cHM6Ly9iaXRjb2luLm9y=
Zy9iaXRjb2luLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe42d3722" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Bitcoin white=
 paper</a>=C2=A0addresses the problem: Sure, anyone can type numbers on the=
ir computer, but is there a way for a community to allocate numbers on your=
 computer=C2=A0in a way that makes them demonstrably scarce? If there is, t=
hen you can call those numbers =E2=80=9Cmoney=E2=80=9D and they can be valu=
able. I am being a little annoying, but this was obviously a real innovatio=
n and did in fact help make=C2=A0Bitcoin very valuable.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rest of the crypto world continued applying that s=
ame process. Most non-fungible token projects address the problem: Sure, an=
yone can limitlessly reproduce JPEGs on the internet, but is there a way fo=
r a community to allocate ownership claims to JPEGs in a way that makes the=
m scarce? The answer is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not really, no, in=C2=A0the sense th=
at anyone can still <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/25879753.286657/aHR0cHM6Ly9zbGF0ZS5jb20vdGVjaG5vbG9neS8yMDIxLzExL25mdC1pb=
WFnZS1vd25lcnNoaXAtcmlnaHQtY2xpY2tpbmctc2F2aW5nLWNvcHlpbmctdHJvbGxpbmcuaHRt=
bA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ec7b9cc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">right-click</a> and save the =
JPEGs underlying most of the popular NFT projects. And yet the answer is al=
so =E2=80=9Csort of,=E2=80=9D in the sense that NFT communities tend to res=
pect the allocations of ownership claims; they=C2=A0<em>act like=C2=A0</em>=
the JPEGs are scarce =E2=80=94=C2=A0the NFTs, the ownership claims,=C2=A0<e=
m>are=C2=A0</em>scarce =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so they have value. And so some N=
FTs sell for lots of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically it is=
 easy, using blockchain technology,=C2=A0to create=C2=A0<em>scarce claims</=
em>. You could I suppose use this technology to create scarce claims to sca=
rce resources: You could put, like, housing deeds or shares of corporate ow=
nership=C2=A0or cargo-container manifests on the blockchain. This would =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0people have argued for years=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0have benefits =
in terms of efficiency and legibility and tradability. It would create valu=
e by improving the processes by which real-world assets are transferred and=
 allocated. Classic financial-services stuff. Nobody talks that=C2=A0much a=
bout this anymore.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, people like to =
use blockchain technology to create scarce claims to=C2=A0<em>abundant</em>=
, or=C2=A0<em>infinite</em>, resources. There is absolutely no shortage of =
JPEGs, they are infinitely reproducible more or less for free, but that mea=
ns =E2=80=94 or meant =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you couldn=E2=80=99t become a mil=
lionaire by having good taste in JPEGs. But now people can create a unique =
non-fungible token=C2=A0representing ownership of a JPEG and use it as a st=
atus symbol or a speculative asset. Nobody will pay you for a number in you=
r computer=E2=80=99s memory, but people will pay you for a=C2=A0<em>scarce=
=C2=A0</em>number in your computer=E2=80=99s memory.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">It is an interesting economic question whether this artificial pr=
oduction of scarcity could actually create value.=C2=A0Arguably abundance i=
s more valuable than scarcity? Arguably this is all =E2=80=A6=C2=A0terrible=
? <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25879753.286657/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ2FyYmFnZWRheS5lbWFpbC9wL3JpZ2h0LWNsaWNrZXJzLXZzLXRoZS1tb25=
rZXktanBn/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7a2dfb78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here is Ryan Broderick=
</a> on crypto, Web3, right-clicking on NFT JPEGs, etc.:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The best overall articulation I=E2=80=99ve seen s=
o far of why Web3 is so hated by many online subcultures right now was from=
 @nicodotgay, the Twitter user behind the right-click mosaic. They explaine=
d in a follow-up tweet that they weren=E2=80=99t anti-NFT for ecological re=
asons. =E2=80=9CThe real issue is that they represent an attempt to re-impo=
se artificial scarcity on culture,=E2=80=9D @nicodotgay tweeted. =E2=80=9C=
=E2=80=98Digital scarcity=E2=80=99 is an anti human evolution ideology that=
 imposes board game-like rules which serve no purpose than to preserve the =
game itself - to hide the internal contradictions of capitalism that become=
 painfully obvious in an area of culture that has overcome scarcity.=E2=80=
=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the other way to put t=
hat is that people do seem to enjoy status-competition and gambling games, =
they get some value out of them, and artificial scarcity allows them to pla=
y a lot more of those games, thus increasing human happiness, or something.=
 There is a new abundance of scarcity.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Simi=
larly. There is a new coronavirus <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/25879753.286657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2hvLmludC9uZXdzL2l0ZW0vMjY=
