om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Derivatives</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday Francine McKenna <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25879753.286657/aHR0cHM6Ly90a=
GVkaWcuc3Vic3RhY2suY29tL3AvcHdjLWJldHdlZW4tYS1yb2NrLWFuZC1hLWhhcmQtcGxhY2U/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7bf1b0ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote=C2=A0about</a> the dispute=
 between Tesla Inc. and JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. over some Tesla warrants t=
hat we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25879753.28=
6657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMT=
YvanBtb3JnYW4tZmlnaHRzLXRlc2xhLW92ZXItd2FycmFudHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEzMDIxX01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjExMTMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB05a77879"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> discussed a couple of weeks ago</a>. Her main point is that JPMor=
gan=C2=A0valued the warrants at one price (assuming that they were adjusted=
 for Elon Musk=E2=80=99s pretend takeover of Tesla), Tesla valued them at s=
ome other price (assuming that they weren=E2=80=99t), they are now in a leg=
al fight over who was right, and PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP audits both com=
panies=E2=80=99 books and presumably let them both use their own differing =
valuations. This actually does not bother me that much =E2=80=94=C2=A0somet=
imes companies get in valuation disputes, and anyway Tesla and JPMorgan acc=
ount for Tesla warrants differently (JPMorgan as a mark-to-market asset, Te=
sla as an equity instrument) =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that=E2=80=99s not what I w=
ant to talk about.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead I want to talk a=
bout this sentence describing the initial 2014 transaction that Tesla and J=
PMorgan are now fighting over: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s one of those =E2=80=98=
heads I win, tails you lose=E2=80=99 type of deals investment banks talk se=
emingly sophisticated company treasurers into.=E2=80=9D I disagree! JPMorga=
n=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>adjustment=C2=A0</em>of the warrants is controversial =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0Tesla thinks it was pretty opportunistic, and I have some sy=
mpathy for that position =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the original deal was fine. Tes=
la paid its banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0JPMorgan and three other underwriters on i=
ts 2014 convertible-bond deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0a net premium of about $214 mi=
llion for the transaction[4]; in exchange, Tesla got a =E2=80=9Cbond hedge=
=E2=80=9D (an option to buy its stock at the conversion price of the conver=
tible bond) and the banks got a warrant=C2=A0(an option to buy the stock at=
 a higher price). Net, Tesla bought a call spread on its own stock. By the =
2021 maturity of=C2=A0the=C2=A0convertible bonds, the stock was way above t=
he exercise prices of all of the options, and Tesla saved something like $7=
60 million worth of stock issuance because of the call spread.[5] Now JPMor=
gan wants $160 million of that back, but even so it was a good deal=C2=A0fo=
r Tesla. (The banks did fine too, they were hedged, don=E2=80=99t worry abo=
ut them.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it gets better. The net premi=
um that Tesla paid to the banks was about $214 million. As we <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25879753.286657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMjMvYW1lcmljYW4tZXhwcm=
Vzcy1zb2xkLXNvbWUtdGF4LWRlZHVjdGlvbnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEzMDIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmd=
XRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTMwJnV0=
bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d14b724" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> di=
scussed last week</a>, that number is conveniently almost exactly the amoun=
t of taxes that Tesla could theoretically save by doing this transaction: T=
he price it paid for the bond hedge (about $603 million) was tax-deductible=
, while the price the banks paid it for the warrants (about $389 million) w=
as not taxable; at a 35% tax rate that $603 million deduction should be wor=
th about $211 million. In practice Tesla has mostly generated losses since =
2014, and probably didn=E2=80=99t get to take a lot of those tax deductions=
; also corporate tax rates are lower now. <em>In general</em>, though, this=
 is the sort of transaction that could reasonably have been marketed as =E2=
=80=9Cyou buy an option from us and the IRS pays for it.=E2=80=9D</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am harping on this because I think it is a general=
 theme in the analysis of complicated financial transactions. In general, w=
hen you see a bank sell a complex derivative to a non-financial customer li=
ke a car company,=C2=A0there are two popular ways to analyze it:</p><ol sty=
le=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The <em>textbook view=C2=A0</em>is that the =
company has some financial risk and is paying the bank a fair premium to ma=
nage the risk. =E2=80=9CTesla has a risk that its stock will go up above th=
e conversion price, so it paid its banks to hedge that risk.=E2=80=9D (It i=
s right in the name, =E2=80=9Cbond hedge.=E2=80=9D)</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">The=C2=A0<em>cynical view=C2=A0</em>is that the bank has =
tricked the customer into giving the bank a lot of money for a worthless th=
ing that the customer doesn=E2=80=99t understand, that the way the bank mak=
es money is by bamboozling the client in a zero-sum trade.</li></ol><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think you should be suspicious of both of those vie=
ws. In many cases the=C2=A0<em>correct, though also cynical=C2=A0</em>view =
is that the trade is, deep down, a=C2=A0tax optimization: The bank does stu=
ff to lower the customer=E2=80=99s taxes, and the customer gives the bank a=
 cut of the tax savings.[6]</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" borde=
